  name: Advection
  title: Advection
  lead: Transport of water or air along with its properties (e.g., temperature, chemical tracers) by winds or currents. Regarding the general distinction between advection and convection, the former describes...
  term *Advection
    # extend Glossary

    insert text
      | Transport of water or air along with its properties (e.g., temperature, chemical tracers) by winds or currents. Regarding the general distinction between {Glossary.*Advection advection} and {Glossary.*Convection convection}, the former describes transport by large-scale motions of the {Topics.*Climate_System atmosphere} or ocean, while convection describes the predominantly vertical, locally induced motions.



  name: Aerosol
  title: Aerosol
  lead: A suspension of airborne solid or liquid particles, with a typical size between a few nanometres and 10 μm that reside in the atmosphere for at least several hours. For convenience the term aerosol, w...
  term *Aerosol
    # extend Glossary

    insert text
      | A suspension of airborne solid or liquid particles, with a typical size between a few nanometres and 10 μm that reside in the {Topics.*Climate_System atmosphere} for at least several hours. For convenience the term aerosol, which includes both the particles and the suspending gas, is often used in this report in its plural form to mean aerosol particles. Aerosols may be of either natural or {Glossary.*Anthropogenic anthropogenic} origin. Aerosols may influence climate in several ways: directly through scattering and absorbing radiation (see {Glossary.*Aerosol Aerosol}–radiation interaction) and indirectly by acting as {Glossary.*Cloud_condensation_nuclei cloud condensation nuclei} or ice nuclei, modifying the optical properties and {Glossary.*Lifetime lifetime} of clouds (see {Glossary.*Aerosol_cloud_interaction Aerosol–cloud interaction}).



  name: Aerosol–cloud interaction
  title: Aerosol–cloud interaction
  lead: A process by which a perturbation to aerosol affects the microphysical properties and evolution of clouds through the aerosol role as cloud condensation nuclei or ice nuclei, particularly in ways that...
  term *Aerosol_cloud_interaction
    # extend Glossary

    insert text
      | A process by which a perturbation to {Glossary.*Aerosol aerosol} affects the microphysical properties and evolution of clouds through the aerosol role as {Glossary.*Cloud_condensation_nuclei cloud condensation nuclei} or ice nuclei, particularly in ways that affect radiation or precipitation; such processes can also include the effect of clouds and precipitation on aerosol. The aerosol perturbation can be {Glossary.*Anthropogenic anthropogenic} or come from some natural {Glossary.*Source source}. The {Topics.*Radiative_Forcing radiative forcing} from such interactions has traditionally been {Topics.*Attribution_of_Change attributed} to numerous indirect aerosol effects, but in this report, only two levels of radiative forcing (or effect) are distinguished:

    include
      - *Radiative_forcing_due_to_aerosol_cloud_interactions
      - *Effective_radiative_forcing_due_to_aerosol_cloud_interactions


  name: RFaci
  title: Radiative forcing due to aerosol–cloud interactions
  lead: The radiative forcing (or radiative effect, if the perturbation is internally generated) due to the change in number or size distribution of cloud droplets or ice crystals that is the proximate result...
  term *Radiative_forcing_due_to_aerosol_cloud_interactions
    # extend *Aerosol_cloud_interaction

    insert text
      | The radiative forcing (or radiative effect, if the perturbation is internally generated) due to the change in number or size distribution of cloud droplets or ice crystals that is the proximate result of an aerosol perturbation, with other variables (in particular total cloud water content) remaining equal. In liquid clouds, an increase in cloud droplet concentration and surface area would increase the cloud albedo. This effect is also known as the cloud albedo effect, first indirect effect, or Twomey effect. It is a largely theoretical concept that cannot readily be isolated in observations or comprehensive process models due to the rapidity and ubiquity of rapid adjustments.



  name: ERFaci
  title: Effective radiative forcing due to aerosol–cloud interactions
  lead: The final radiative forcing (or effect) from the aerosol perturbation including the rapid adjustments to the initial change in droplet or crystal formation rate. These adjustments include changes in t...
  term *Effective_radiative_forcing_due_to_aerosol_cloud_interactions
    # extend *Aerosol_cloud_interaction

    insert text
      | The final radiative forcing (or effect) from the aerosol perturbation including the rapid adjustments to the initial change in droplet or crystal formation rate. These adjustments include changes in the strength of convection, precipitation efficiency, cloud fraction, lifetime or water content of clouds, and the formation or suppression of clouds in remote areas due to altered circulations.
      | The total effective radiative forcing due to both aerosol–cloud and aerosol–radiation interactions is denoted aerosol effective radiative forcing (ERFari+aci).


    name: See Also
    embed
      - *Aerosol_radiation_interaction

