  name: Climate change
  title: Climate change
  lead: Climate change refers to a change in the state of the climate that can be identified (e.g., by using statistical tests) by changes in the mean and/or the variability of its properties, and that persis...
  term *Climate_change
    # extend Glossary

    insert text
      | Climate change refers to a change in the state of the climate that can be identified (e.g., by using statistical tests) by changes in the mean and/or the variability of its properties, and that persists for an extended period, typically decades or longer. Climate change may be due to natural internal processes or {Topics.*Radiative_Forcing external forcings} such as modulations of the solar cycles, volcanic eruptions and persistent {Glossary.*Anthropogenic anthropogenic} changes in the composition of the {Topics.*Climate_System atmosphere} or in land use. Note that the {Glossary.*Framework_Convention_on_Climate_Change Framework Convention on Climate Change} ({Glossary.*United_Nations_Framework_Convention_on_Climate_Change UNFCCC}), in its Article 1, defines climate change as: ‘a change of climate which is {Topics.*Attribution_of_Change attributed} directly or indirectly to human activity that alters the composition of the global {Glossary.*Atmosphere atmosphere} and which is in addition to natural {Topics.*Climate_Variability climate variability} observed over comparable time periods’. The UNFCCC thus makes a distinction between climate change attributable to {Topics.*Human_Influence human activities} altering the atmospheric composition, and climate variability attributable to natural causes.


