      | In IPCC reports, equilibrium {Glossary.*Climate_sensitivity climate sensitivity} (units: °C) refers to the equilibrium (steady state) change in the annual global mean {Topics.*Surface_Temperature surface temperature} following a doubling of the atmospheric equivalent {Glossary.*Carbon_dioxide carbon dioxide} concentration. Owing to computational constraints, the {Glossary.*Equilibrium_climate_sensitivity equilibrium climate sensitivity} in a {Topics.*Climate_Modelling climate model} is sometimes estimated by running an atmospheric {Glossary.*General_circulation general circulation} model coupled to a mixed-layer ocean model, because equilibrium climate sensitivity is largely determined by atmospheric processes. Efficient models can be run to equilibrium with a dynamic ocean. The {Glossary.*Climate_sensitivity_parameter climate sensitivity parameter} (units: °C (W m–2)–1) refers to the equilibrium change in the annual global mean {Glossary.*Surface_temperature surface temperature} following a unit change in {Topics.*Radiative_Forcing radiative forcing}.



