  name: ENSO
  title: El Niño-Southern Oscillation
  lead: The term El Niño was initially used to describe a warm-water current that periodically flows along the coast of Ecuador and Peru, disrupting the local fishery. It has since become identified with a b...
  term *El_Nin_o_Southern_Oscillation
    # extend Glossary

    insert text
      | The term El Niño was initially used to describe a warm-water current that periodically flows along the coast of Ecuador and Peru, disrupting the local fishery. It has since become identified with a basin-wide warming of the tropical Pacific Ocean east of the dateline. This oceanic event is associated with a fluctuation of a globalscale tropical and subtropical surface pressure pattern called the {Glossary.*Southern_Oscillation Southern Oscillation}. This coupled {Topics.*Climate_System atmosphere}–ocean phenomenon, with preferred time scales of two to about seven years, is known as the El Niño-Southern Oscillation ({Glossary.*El_Nin_o_Southern_Oscillation ENSO}). It is often measured by the surface pressure anomaly difference between Tahiti and Darwin or the sea {Topics.*Surface_Temperature surface temperatures} in the central and eastern equatorial Pacific. During an ENSO event, the prevailing trade winds weaken, reducing upwelling and altering ocean currents such that the sea surface temperatures warm, further weakening the trade winds. This event has a great impact on the wind, sea {Glossary.*Surface_temperature surface temperature} and precipitation patterns in the tropical Pacific. It has climatic effects throughout the Pacific {Topics.*Regional_Climate region} and in many other parts of the world, through global teleconnections. The cold phase of ENSO is called {Glossary.*La_Nin_a La Niña}. For the corresponding indices, see {Box_2_5 Box 2.5}.



  name: Emission scenario
  title: Emission scenario
  lead: A plausible representation of the future development of emissions of substances that are potentially radiatively active (e.g., greenhouse gases, aerosols) based on a coherent and internally consistent...
  term *Emission_scenario
    # extend Glossary

    insert text
      | A plausible representation of the future development of {Topics.*Emissions emissions} of substances that are potentially radiatively active (e.g., greenhouse gases, aerosols) based on a coherent and internally consistent set of assumptions about driving forces (such as demographic and socioeconomic development, technological change) and their key relationships. Concentration scenarios, derived from emission scenarios, are used as input to a {Topics.*Climate_Modelling climate model} to compute climate {Topics.*Climate_Projections projections}. In {cite.Glossary.'IPCC_1992 IPCC (1992)} a set of emission scenarios was presented which were used as a basis for the climate projections in {cite.Glossary.'IPCC_1996 IPCC (1996)}. These emission scenarios are referred to as the IS92 scenarios. In the IPCC Special Report on Emission {Topics.*Scenarios Scenarios} (Nakićenović and {cite.Glossary.'Swart_2000}) emission scenarios, the so-called {Glossary.*SRES_scenarios SRES scenarios}, were published, some of which were used, among others, as a basis for the climate projections presented in {Chapters.9 Chapter 9} to 11 of {cite.Glossary.'IPCC_2001 IPCC (2001)} and Chapters 10 and 11 of {cite.Glossary.'IPCC_2007 IPCC (2007)}. New emission scenarios for climate change, the four {Glossary.*Representative_Concentration_Pathways Representative Concentration Pathways}, were developed for, but independently of, the present IPCC assessment.


