  name: Greenhouse effect
  title: Greenhouse effect
  lead: The infrared radiative effect of all infrared-absorbing constituents in the atmosphere. Greenhouse gases, clouds, and (to a small extent) aerosols absorb terrestrial radiation emitted by the Earth’s s...
  term *Greenhouse_effect
    # extend Glossary

    insert text
      | The infrared {Glossary.*Radiative_effect radiative effect} of all infrared-absorbing constituents in the {Topics.*Climate_System atmosphere}. Greenhouse gases, clouds, and (to a small extent) aerosols absorb {Glossary.*Terrestrial_radiation terrestrial radiation} emitted by the Earth’s surface and elsewhere in the {Glossary.*Atmosphere atmosphere}. These substances emit {Glossary.*Infrared_radiation infrared radiation} in all directions, but, everything else being equal, the net amount emitted to space is normally less than would have been emitted in the absence of these absorbers because of the decline of temperature with altitude in the {Glossary.*Troposphere troposphere} and the consequent weakening of emission. An increase in the concentration of greenhouse gases increases the magnitude of this effect; the difference is sometimes called the enhanced {Glossary.*Greenhouse_effect greenhouse effect}. The change in a {Glossary.*Greenhouse_gas greenhouse gas} concentration because of {Glossary.*Anthropogenic anthropogenic} {Topics.*Emissions emissions} contributes to an instantaneous {Topics.*Radiative_Forcing radiative forcing}. {Glossary.*Surface_temperature Surface temperature} and troposphere warm in response to this forcing, gradually restoring the radiative balance at the top of the atmosphere.



  name: Greenhouse gas
