      | Greenhouse gases are those gaseous constituents of the {Topics.*Climate_System atmosphere}, both natural and {Glossary.*Anthropogenic anthropogenic}, that absorb and emit radiation at specific wavelengths within the spectrum of {Glossary.*Terrestrial_radiation terrestrial radiation} emitted by the Earth’s surface, the {Glossary.*Atmosphere atmosphere} itself, and by clouds. This property causes the {Glossary.*Greenhouse_effect greenhouse effect}. Water vapour (H2O), carbon dioxide ({Glossary.*Carbon_dioxide CO2}), nitrous oxide ({Glossary.*Nitrous_oxide_N2O N2O}), methane ({Glossary.*Methane_CH4 CH4}) and {Glossary.*Ozone ozone} (O3) are the primary greenhouse gases in the Earth’s atmosphere. Moreover, there are a number of entirely human-made greenhouse gases in the atmosphere, such as the {Glossary.*Halocarbons halocarbons} and other chlorineand brominecontaining substances, dealt with under the {Glossary.*Montreal_Protocol Montreal Protocol}. Beside CO2, N2O and CH4, the {Glossary.*Kyoto_Protocol Kyoto Protocol} deals with the greenhouse gases sulphur hexafluoride (SF6), hydrofluorocarbons (HFCs) and perfluorocarbons (PFCs). For a list of well-mixed greenhouse gases, see Table 2.A.1.



