  name: NTCF
  title: Near-term climate forcers
  lead: Near-term climate forcers (NTCF) refer to those compounds whose impact on climate occurs primarily within the first decade after their emission. This set of compounds is primarily composed of those wi...
  term *Near_term_climate_forcers
    # extend Glossary

    insert text
      | Near-term climate forcers ({Glossary.*Near_term_climate_forcers NTCF}) refer to those compounds whose impact on climate occurs primarily within the first decade after their {Topics.*Emissions emission}. This set of compounds is primarily composed of those with short lifetimes in the {Topics.*Climate_System atmosphere} compared to well-mixed greenhouse gases, and has been sometimes referred to as short lived climate forcers or short-lived climate pollutants. However, the common property that is of greatest interest to a climate assessment is the timescale over which their impact on climate is felt. This set of compounds includes methane, which is also a well-mixed {Glossary.*Greenhouse_gas greenhouse gas}, as well as {Glossary.*Ozone ozone} and aerosols, or their {Glossary.*Precursors precursors}, and some halogenated species that are not well-mixed greenhouse gases. These compounds do not accumulate in the {Glossary.*Atmosphere atmosphere} at decadal to centennial timescales, and so their effect on climate is predominantly in the near term following their emission.



