  name: Radiative effect
  title: Radiative effect
  lead: The impact on a radiation flux or heating rate (most commonly, on the downward flux at the top of atmosphere) caused by the interaction of a particular constituent with either the infrared or solar ra...
  term *Radiative_effect
    # extend Glossary

    insert text
      | The impact on a radiation flux or heating rate (most commonly, on the downward flux at the top of {Topics.*Climate_System atmosphere}) caused by the interaction of a particular constituent with either the infrared or {Glossary.*Solar_radiation solar radiation} fields through absorption, scattering and {Topics.*Emissions emission}, relative to an otherwise identical {Glossary.*Atmosphere atmosphere} free of that constituent. This quantifies the impact of the constituent on the climate system. Examples include the {Glossary.*Aerosol aerosol}–radiation interactions, cloud {Glossary.*Radiative_effect radiative effect}, and {Glossary.*Greenhouse_effect greenhouse effect}. In this report, the portion of any top-of-atmosphere radiative effect that is due to {Glossary.*Anthropogenic anthropogenic} or other external influences (e.g., volcanic eruptions or changes in the sun) is termed the instantaneous {Topics.*Radiative_Forcing radiative forcing}.



  name: Radiative forcing
  title: Radiative forcing
  lead: Radiative forcing is the change in the net, downward minus upward, radiative flux (expressed in W m–2) at the tropopause or top of atmosphere due to a change in an external driver of climate change, s...
  term *Radiative_forcing
    # extend Glossary

    insert text
      | Radiative forcing is the change in the net, downward minus upward, radiative flux (expressed in W m–2) at the {Glossary.*Tropopause tropopause} or top of {Topics.*Climate_System atmosphere} due to a change in an external driver of climate change, such as, for example, a change in the concentration of {Glossary.*Carbon_dioxide carbon dioxide} or the output of the Sun. Sometimes internal drivers are still treated as forcings even though they result from the alteration in climate, for example {Glossary.*Aerosol aerosol} or {Glossary.*Greenhouse_gas greenhouse gas} changes in paleoclimates. The traditional {Topics.*Radiative_Forcing radiative forcing} is computed with all tropospheric properties held fixed at their unperturbed values, and after allowing for stratospheric temperatures, if perturbed, to readjust to radiative-dynamical equilibrium. Radiative forcing is called instantaneous if no change in stratospheric temperature is accounted for. The radiative forcing once rapid adjustments are accounted for is termed the {Glossary.*Effective_radiative_forcing effective radiative forcing}. For the purposes of this report, radiative forcing is further defined as the change relative to the year 1750 and, unless otherwise noted, refers to a global and annual average value. Radiative forcing is not to be confused with cloud radiative forcing, which describes an unrelated measure of the impact of clouds on the radiative flux at the top of the {Glossary.*Atmosphere atmosphere}.



  name: Rapid adjustment
  title: Rapid adjustment
  lead: The response to an agent perturbing the climate system that is driven directly by the agent, independently of any change in the global mean surface temperature. For example, carbon dioxide and aerosol...
  term *Rapid_adjustment
    # extend Glossary

    insert text
      | The response to an agent perturbing the climate system that is driven directly by the agent, independently of any change in the global mean {Topics.*Surface_Temperature surface temperature}. For example, {Glossary.*Carbon_dioxide carbon dioxide} and aerosols, by altering internal heating and cooling rates within the {Topics.*Climate_System atmosphere}, can each cause changes to cloud cover and other variables thereby producing a {Glossary.*Radiative_effect radiative effect} even in the absence of any surface warming or cooling. Adjustments are rapid in the sense that they begin to occur right away, before climate feedbacks which are driven by warming (although some adjustments may still take significant time to proceed to completion, for example those involving vegetation or ice sheets). It is also called the rapid response or fast adjustment. For further explanation on the concept, see Sections {Chapters.7.7_1 7.1} and {Chapters.8.8_1 8.1}.



