  lead: The response time or adjustment time is the time needed for the climate system or its components to re-equilibrate to a new state, following a forcing resulting from external processes. It is very dif...
  term *Response_time
    # extend Glossary

    insert text
      | The {Glossary.*Adjustment_time_or_response_time_Ta response time} or adjustment time is the time needed for the climate system or its components to re-equilibrate to a new state, following a {Topics.*Radiative_Forcing forcing} resulting from external processes. It is very different for various components of the climate system. The {Glossary.*Response_time response time} of the {Glossary.*Troposphere troposphere} is relatively short, from days to weeks, whereas the {Glossary.*Stratosphere stratosphere} reaches equilibrium on a time scale of typically a few months. Due to their large heat capacity, the oceans have a much longer response time: typically decades, but up to centuries or millennia. The response time of the strongly coupled surface–troposphere system is, therefore, slow compared to that of the stratosphere, and mainly determined by the oceans. The {Topics.*Climate_System biosphere} may respond quickly (e.g., to droughts), but also very slowly to imposed changes. See {Glossary.*Lifetime lifetime} for a different definition of response time pertinent to the rate of processes affecting the concentration of trace gases.



